        <body>       
                
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Hebrew Sunday&#45;School Society.<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia&#44; Nov. 19&#47;88<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Mr. Morais.<lb/></p>
            <p>I was sorry<lb/> not to meet you in School<lb/> yesterday&#45;&#45;I get to 7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.<lb/> just after you left.  I had<lb/> word from Dr. Adler that<lb/> he would <del>approve of</del> recommend Lady<lb/> Magnus&#39; book for temporary<lb/> use merely and that it<lb/> would have to be imparted.<lb/>  This latter fact&#44; if no<lb/> other&#44; makes the use of<lb/> this book&#44; out of the question<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>for the present.  Our Committee<lb/> on Textbooks&#44; had a con&#45;<lb/>ference and decided that<lb/> the most available book<lb/> for immediate use&#44; would<lb/> be that of Dr. Mendes.<lb/>  Miss Allen told me that<lb/> you had no copy of Lady Mag&#45;<lb/>nus&#39; book.  Do you know<lb/> anything of &#34;<hi rend="underline">Abarbanels</hi>&#39;<lb/> Reader&#34;&#63;  I just glanced<lb/> through it&#44; but it seemed to<lb/> me to have much information<lb/> that would be useful to a<lb/> teacher.  Yours very truly<lb/> C. Kahn.<lb/> Ch<hi rend="sup">n</hi>. Co<hi rend="sup">m</hi>.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
